---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="New Deck Builds | Custom Design & Construction | Belvedere Decks"
  description="New composite deck construction in Maryland: designed, engineered, permitted, and inspected. $25,000–$75,000+ typical. One design visit that ends with drawings and a fixed price."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">New Deck Builds · $25,000–$75,000+</p>
      <h1>Designed around how you actually live outside.</h1>
      <div class="rule"></div>
      <p class="lead">
        Dinners for twelve or quiet coffee for two: how you use your yard drives the
        design more than anything. We design and build fully custom decks, and we also
        tear out old decks and build new from the ground up. Every build is engineered,
        permitted, and inspected.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>One visit is usually all it takes</h2>
      <p>
        We walk your yard together: how you'll use the space, the views, the sun, the
        slope, and any HOA rules. We measure, photograph, and agree on a realistic
        budget range out loud, no games. Then we design your deck and build the price
        right there with you: three complete versions, priced exactly, every question
        answered in person. If your project needs engineering review or HOA drawings
        before the numbers can be final, we schedule one follow-up visit to present
        them. That is the exception, not the process.
      </p>

      <h2>How we build</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>We pull the building permit and prepare your HOA paperwork, with fees included in the quote</li>
        <li>Miss Utility marks underground lines before any digging</li>
        <li>Concrete footings dug 30 inches deep (below the frost line, sized to code) and inspected by the county before we pour</li>
        <li>Pressure-treated 6x6 posts on galvanized bases; the board that attaches the deck to your house (the ledger) is bolted to the framing with waterproof flashing behind it, so water never gets into your house wall</li>
        <li>The support frame (the joists) set 12 inches apart, closer than code requires, so composite boards never sag</li>
        <li>Steel connectors at every joint, with every fastener hole filled, including the ties that keep the deck from ever pulling away from the house</li>
        <li>County framing inspection passed before a single board goes down</li>
        <li>Waterproof tape on top of every frame board, premium decking with no screw heads underfoot, a bordered edge (like a picture frame around your deck), and clean trim wrapping the sides</li>
        <li>Code-safe stairs with lighting where selected</li>
        <li>Final county inspection passed, site cleaned, everything hauled away</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- STOCK PHOTO SLOT: manufacturer imagery is OK on this page (never on Our Work).
           Download from the TrexPro / TimberTech partner portals after registering, save to
           /public/images/, then uncomment. Keep the courtesy caption - it keeps things honest.
      <figure style="margin: 2rem 0;">
        <img src="/images/trex-new-build.jpg" alt="Composite deck built with Trex decking"
          style="width: 100%; border-radius: var(--radius); box-shadow: var(--shadow-medium);" />
        <figcaption style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--muted-foreground); margin-top: 6px;">
          Photo courtesy of Trex® — shown for product reference.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      -->

      <h2>Same structure, every tier</h2>
      <p>
        Good, better, and best differ in boards, railings, and details, never in the
        structure. We don't tier the safety, and we'll show you exactly what that means
        standing under your own deck.
      </p>
      <p><a class="btn primary" href="/estimate">Get a Free Estimate</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
